text:
Tiles and Tools

Text

When you click into a text tile in your workspace, a tray with icons for editing options appears below it. Hover your mouse over the items in the tray for more information (and a keyboard shortcut) about each. Go ahead and make a text tile now, and write down what you're most looking forward to learning about CLUE and STEM. Be sure to try some formatting, highlighting and list options.

Tables and Data Cards

Tables and Data Cards are both handy ways of holding on to information. They can be used to record data, document steps, or even hold images of your data. Tables in CLUE can hold text if you want to describe something, dates, and even expressions to calculate data values, like the velocity calculation in the table below. Table columns can be sorted and table rows can be rearranged to show your data any way you'd like.

Try making a new table in your workspace that has the foods you ate for breakfast this week, the date you ate them, what food group they are in, and the calories you think they contained. Once you have some data in your table, choose the DataCard It! table tool to see the same data in a different way.

Graphs and Grids

There are several kinds of graphs in CLUE, one for showing X-Y data, shown below, one for showing categories as bars, and one for showing closed shapes that we call a Grid. Notice that the same table you made has options for Graph It! and BarGraph It! and Grid It! Give these tools a try and see what you get.

tiles.title: A graph of the table data

text:
Sketching

You can convey a lot of information in a Sketch. You can draw a picture of your solution. You can use repeated shapes and arrangements to model a solution or system. You can put an image into a sketch and annotate it with the sketch tools. Images could be something you looked up, a photo you take of an experiment or scene, or a screen capture of your own work to document it.

Make a Sketch in your workspace now. Add three shapes and align them. Add at least one image using the upload button in the tool set or copy an image to the clipboard and use Ctrl-V to paste it in the target sketch tile.

Of course, you can always drag an sketch into your workspace and keep going.

Here's a sketch to play with.

Annotation Arrows (SPArrows)

There's a special feature in CLUE that lets you show relationships between objects either in your tiles or across them. These arrows are made using the blue comment arrow bubble at the top of your workspace. Then you can click on any two objects and talk about the relationship between them. Try making some sparrows in your workspace. You can connect cells in tables, points in graphs, and shapes in sketches, as well as highlighted textinvalid reference: 5e1f5da9-30a7-4180-afb0-6c8f464b6c03.

Those are the basics. There are many more tools in CLUE that can allow you to work with equations, program sensors and simulations, write questions, and more. We'll cover these in more detail in future Lessons. For now congratulations on a job well done - you made your first CLUE workspace! Move on the Reflect tab.
